{"title_page": "William Farrar (settler)", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{short description|Early settler, member of the Virginia Council, and Commissioner in the Virginia colony}}{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}} \n{{infobox person\n| name               = William Farrar\n| birth_date         = April 1583\n| birth_place        = [[Croxton, Lincolnshire]], England\n| death_date         = c.\u20091637\n| death_place        = [[Colonial Virginia]]\n| spouse             = [[Cecily Jordan Farrar|Cecily Jordan]]\n| occupation         = Councillor - [[Virginia Governor's Council|Council of Virginia]] and [[Virginia General Assembly]]\n}}\n\n'''William Farrar''' (April 1583 \u2013 {{Circa|1637}}) was an early [[settler]], [[Land tenure|landholder]], and [[legislator]] of the [[Colony of Virginia]]. He was a subscriber to the third charter of the [[Virginia Company]] who emigrated to the colony in 1618. After surviving the [[Powhatan attack of 1622]], he moved to [[Jordan Point, Virginia|Jordan's Journey]]. In the following year, Farrar became involved in North America's first breach of promise suit when he proposed to [[Cecily Jordan Farrar|Cecily Jordan]].  In 1626, Farrar was appointed to the [[Virginia Governor's Council|Council of Virginia]] where he served as an advisor to the royal governor, a judge of the highest court in the colony, and a member of the [[Virginia General Assembly]] of [[Colonial Jamestown]]. He was also appointed magistrate of the upper James River community. In both these roles, he served as a voice of the early planters' interest as the colony transitioned from being managed by the Virginia Company and becoming a royal colony under [[Charles I of England]]. Farrar was also on the Council when it arrested Governor [[John Harvey (Virginia)|John Harvey]] for misgovernance and forced his temporary return to England. By the time of his death around 1637, Farrar had sold off his remaining assets in England and established rights to a 2000 acre patent on [[Farrar's Island]], located on a curl of the James River.\n\n[[File:Farrar Complete Coat of Arms.jpg|thumb|The [[Coat of arms|arms]] of William Farrar's father, John Farrar of Croxton and London, Esquire<ref name= Bannerman1899/>]]\n\n==Background==\nWilliam Farrar was born before April 28, 1583,<ref name=\"Dorman2004\" /> the date of his christening, in [[Croxton, Lincolnshire]], England.<ref name=CroxtonParish1583 /> He was the 3rd son of John Farrar of Croxton<ref name= \"Bannerman1899\" /> and London, [[Esquire]], a wealthy [[merchant]] and [[Land tenure|landowner]] with various holdings in [[West Yorkshire]], [[Lincolnshire]], and [[Hertfordshire]]<ref name =Farrer1936/>, and Cecily Kelke, an heiress <ref name=Richardson2011/> and direct descendant of [[Edward III of England]].<ref name=ElleMagazine2014/> The nineteenth century historian of Virginia, [[Alexander Brown (author)|Alexander Brown]], states that while in England, William Farrar received an education in law.<ref name=Brown1890v2 />\n\n== Relation to the Virginia Company and emigration to the New World ==\n[[File:Nova Britannia Cover.jpg|thumb|left|Facsimile cover of \"Nova Britannia\", a tract from Farrar's time used to recruit people to Virginia.]]\nWhen Farrar went to Virginia, it was still part of the [[Virginia Company of London]], a [[joint-stock company]], sanctioned by [[Royal charter#United Kingdom|Royal Charter]].<ref name=\"Wolfe2016\" /> Farrar was a subscriber to the Third Charter of the Virginia Company,<ref name= Kolp2014 /> where his name appears as \"William Ferrers\".<ref name= Bemiss1957 /> His subscription consisted of three shares that were bought for a total of \u00a337 10s (equivalent to about ${{formatnum:{{ To USD round|{{inflation|UK|37.5|1600}}|GBR|sf=3}}}} today).{{Notetag|For another comparison of the share's value, the entire annual wages of a skilled [[journeyman]] in London around 1588 was authorized to be between \u00a34 and \u00a310. {{refn|name=Aughterson1998}} }}<ref name=Brown1890v2 /> Farrar also had family interests in the Virginia Company as two of his second cousins,<ref name=Torrence1942 /> the brothers [[John Ferrar]] and [[Nicholas Ferrar]], played key roles in the managing the company's interests.<ref name=Kingsbury1906v1/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/recordsofvirgini01virg_0/page/n121/mode/2up 60}} }}\n\nFarrar left London on ''Neptune''<ref name= Hotten1874/> on March 16, 1617/18  {{notetag|[[Dual dating]] is given because the English new year did not begin until March 25 during the time Virginia was colonized.  See article on [[Old Style and New Style dates#Start of the year in the historical records of Britain and its colonies and possessions|dating English historical records]] for details.}}<ref name=\"Kolb1980\" /> along with Virginia's governor, [[Thomas West, 3rd Baron De La Warr|Thomas West, Baron De La Warr]].  De La Warr had been commissioned by the Virginia Company to return to the colony with fresh people and supplies to help it achieve political and economic stability,<ref name=Brown1890v1/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/TheGenesisOfTheUnitedStatesV1/page/n499/mode/2up 375\u2013384}}}} but he died en route.<ref name=\"Billings2013\" /> When Farrar arrived in August 1618,<ref name=\"Hotten1874\"/> news of the governor's death threw [[Jamestown, Virginia|Jamestown]] into turmoil, Deputy Governor [[Samuel Argall]], who was already unpopular with many colonists, was accused of mismanagement and  the unauthorized misappropriation of  ''Neptune'''s passengers and cargo.<ref name=\"Coldham1979\"/> After a prolonged series of accusations from both the Virginia Company and colonists against Argall's governing, he finally stepped down in April 1619.<ref name=Fausz2013/>\n\nIn June 1619, the Virginia Company instructed that 40 [[Indentured Servitude#The Americas|indentured servants]] be put at the disposal of Farrar when they arrived in Virginia.<ref name=Kingsbury1933v3 />{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/recordsofvirgini03virg/page/144/mode/2up 145}} }}  The payment for the cost of transporting these colonists would have resulted in a 2000 acre [[headright]] at 50 acres a head.<ref name=Wolfe&McCartney2015/> However, ''Garland'' never arrived in Jamestown because it was damaged in a hurricane while en route.<ref name=Coldham2002/> Instead of proceeding to Virginia, the ''Garland''{{'}}s captain, William Wye left the remaining passengers in  [[Somers Isles Company|Bermuda]] and sailed the repaired ship directly back to England.<ref name=Kingsbury1906v1 />{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/recordsofvirgini01virg_0/page/n645/mode/2up 325}} }}\n\nAs his personal headright, Farrar did receive a [[land patent]] for 100 acres on the [[Appomattox River]] close to where it flows into the [[James River]], near what is now known as [[Hopewell, Virginia]].<ref name= Kingsbury1935v4 />{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/stream/recordsofvirgini04virg/#page/n591/mode/2up 554}} }} In the meantime,  the resultant legal suits between Wye and  the Virginia Company regarding the financial responsibility for the ''Garland'' fiasco were not resolved until the end of 1622,<ref name=Kingsbury1933v3 />{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/recordsofvirgini03virg/page/700/mode/2up 701\u2013702}}}} <ref name=Coldham2002/> when Farrar had already quit residence at his patent as a result of the [[Powhatan attack of 1622|Powhatan surprise attack of 1621/22]].\n\n== Move to Jordan's Journey and marriage==\n{{see also|Cecily Jordan v. Greville Pooley dispute}}\n\n[[File:1622 massacre jamestown de Bry.jpg|thumb|[[Matth\u00e4us Merian|Matth\u00e4us Merian's]] engraving of the Powhatan surprise attack of 1622, in which 10 people at Farrar's patent were killed.]]\nDuring the Powhatan surprise attack, ten settlers on Farrar's land on the Appomattox River were killed.<ref name=Kingsbury1933v3/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/recordsofvirgini03virg/page/566/mode/2up 566}}}} However, Farrar survived and got to [[Samuel Jordan|Samuel Jordan's]] settlement at [[Jordan Point, Virginia#Beggars Bush|Beggars Bush]],<ref name=MorganEtAl1995/> part of the plantation known as [[Jordan Point, Virginia|Jordan's Journey]]. After the attack, William Farrar stayed at Jordan's Journey<ref name= McCartney2007/>{{rp|{{plainlink|{{Google books|orDbMGpInaQC|page=290|plainurl=yes}} 290\u2013291}} }} as it had become a relatively safe fortified rallying place for the survivors.<ref name=Smith1624/>\n\nSamuel Jordan died before June 1623.<ref name=Sainsbury1860/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/calendarstatepa16offigoog/page/n83/mode/2up 46}} }} Sometime afterward, Farrar proposed marriage to Jordan's pregnant widow, [[Cecily Jordan Farrar|Cecily]], which involved him in the  [[Cecily Jordan v. Greville Pooley dispute|first breach of promise suit filed in North America]].<ref name=Brown1890v2 />{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/genesisofuniteds02brow/page/n455/mode/2up 891}} }} Reverend Greville Pooley claimed he had first proposed marriage three or four days after Samuel Jordan had died and Cecily had accepted.<ref name=Kingsbury1935v4/> However, Cecily denied his proposal and accepted Farrar's, which resulted in Pooley filing the suit.<ref name =Starrett1958/>  The case continued for almost two years. During the suit, Alexander Brown suggests that Farrar may have acted as Cecily's legal representative.<ref name=Brown1890v2/>   Eventually, Pooley signed an agreement in January 1624/5 that acquitted Cecily Jordan of her alleged former promises.<ref name=McIlwaine1924/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/minutesofcouncil00virg/page/42/mode/2up 42}}}}\n\nEven as the case was ongoing, William Farrar and Cecily Jordan continued to work together at Jordan's Journey. In November 1623, Farrar was [[debt bondage|bonded]] to execute Samuel Jordan's will regarding the management of his estate and Cecily Jordan was warranted to put down the security to guarantee Farrar's bondage.<ref name=McIlwaine1924/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/minutesofcouncil00virg/page/8/mode/2up 8}} }} During this time, \"Farrar assumed the role of plantation 'commander' or 'head of hundred'\"<ref name=McLearenEtAl1993/>{{rp|10}} for Jordan's Journey. A year later, the Jamestown muster of 1624/25 lists \"fferrar William mr & Mrs. Jordan\"[sic] as sharing the head of a Jordan's Journey household with three daughters and ten manservants.<ref name=Hotten1874/> During this time, Jordan's Journey prospered.<ref name=Hatch1957/>{{rp|{{plainlink|http://www.gutenberg.org/files/30780/30780-h/30780-h.htm#JORDAN_R 67\u201368}} }}  By May 1625 Farrar and Jordan were finally married, as it was then that Farrar was released from his bond to Jordan's estate.<ref name=McIlwaine1924/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/minutesofcouncil00virg/page/57/mode/2up 57}} }}They had three children together: Cecily (born 1625), William (birth year uncertain), and John (born around 1632).<ref name=Dorman2004/>\n\n== Roles in the governance of the royal colony ==\nOn March 14, 1625/6, William Farrar was appointed councillor to the [[Virginia Governor's Council#Royal colony (1624\u20131776)|Council of Virginia]] by [[Charles I of England]],<ref name=Stanard1906/> a position he held until at least 1635 when Governor [[John Harvey (Virginia)|John Harvey]] was deported.<ref name =Sainsbury1860/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/calendarstatepa16offigoog/page/n249/mode/2up 212\u2013213}} }}\n\n[[File:Seal of Governor's Council.png|thumb|left|Seal of \"His Majesties Council of Virginia\",\n<ref name=Brown1890v1/> the symbol of Farrar and the other councillors' role in Virginia's governance.]]\nFarrar became a councillor during a period of uncertainty for the colonists.<ref name=McCartney2007/>{{rp|{{plainlink|{{Google books|orDbMGpInaQC|page=13|plainurl=yes}} 13,}} {{plainlink|{{Google books|orDbMGpInaQC|page=35|plainurl=yes}} 35}} }} The [[Virginia Company#\"Great Charter\"|1619 Great Charter]] of the Virginia Company had established self-governance through the [[Virginia Assembly]], but [[James I]] dissolved the charter in 1624, and put the colony under direct royal authority. Just before James I died in March 1625, Charles I announced his intention to be the sole [[Factor (agent)|factor]] of his [[royal colony|royal colonies]].<ref name=Bancroft1888/> To this end, he commissioned a new structure, consisting of a governor, [[George Yeardley|Sir George Yeardley]], and 13 councillors, including William Farrar, to govern the royal colony on behalf of the Crown's interest.<ref name=\"Stanard1906\" /> Because the assembly was not included in the commission, the Council was the only legal body representing the interests of the Virginia planters.<ref name=Campbell1860/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/historyofcolonya00campuoft/page/180/mode/2up 180}} }} This state of affairs continued until the petitions of the colonists allowed the continuance of the [[House of Burgesses]] and the re-convention of the Virginia Assembly in 1628.<ref name= \"Brown1898\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/firstrepublicina01brow|title=The First Republic in America|last=Brown|first=Alexander|author-link=Alexander Brown (author)|publisher=Boston, MA: Houghton, Mifflin|year=1898|isbn=|pp=[https://archive.org/details/firstrepublicina01brow/page/645 645]\u2013648}}</ref> The Council also functioned as the highest court in Virginia and as the advisory board to the governor regarding the creation of legislative acts. Just as importantly, the members of the Council could determine the fate of the governor: William Farrar was on the Council when it elected [[John Pott]] as governor in 1628<ref name=Campbell1860/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/historyofcolonya00campuoft/page/182/mode/2up 182}} }} and he was on the Council <ref name=Brown1901/> when it arrested and temporarily deported Governor Harvey in 1635.<ref name=Bruce1894/><ref name=Tarter2017a/>\n\nIn August 1626, Farrar was also appointed by Yeardley as commissioner (i.e., [[magistrate#English common law tradition|magistrate]]) of the \"Upper Partes\"[sic]  which lies along the James River west of [[Flowerdew Hundred Plantation|Piersey's Hundred]] in the approximate area of [[Charles City County, Virginia|Charles City]] and [[Henrico County, Virginia|Henrico]] Counties today. Farrar was one of six commissioners appointed, however he was the one given the right of final judgement when present and allowed the discretion to hold monthly courts at either Jordan's Journey or [[Shirley Plantation|Shirley Hundred]].<ref name=McIlwaine1924/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/minutesofcouncil00virg/page/106/mode/2up 106}} }}.  When Virginia became a crown colony, this appointment was renewed by the Governor [[John Harvey (Virginia)| Sir John Harvey]] in 1632<ref name=Hening1809/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/statutesatlargeb01invirg/page/168 168}}}}\n\n== Sale of inheritance ==\nWhen William Farrar's father, John the elder, died sometime before May 1628, he willed his various landholdings in Hertfordshire to William. In addition, John Farrar also stipulated that William and his family receive a \u00a320 annuity from his older brother from rents in Halifax Parish, Yorkshire and that William receive \u00a350 upon his return to England.<ref name= \"Farrer1936\"/> In 1631,  William Farrar returned to England to claim his inheritance.<ref name=McCartney2007/>  He then sold the assets from his inheritance to his brothers, including his annuity for \u00a3240 and his landholdings for \u00a3200, for a total of \u00a3440 (equivalent to about ${{formatnum:{{ To USD round|{{inflation|UK|440|1600}}|GBR|sf=3}}}} today)<ref name=Holmes1972/> and returned to Virginia.\n\n==Farrar's Island==\n[[File:Map of William Farrar&#039;s Patent for Farrar&#039;s Island and Environs.jpg|thumb|Approximate extent of William Farrar&#039;s 2000-acre land grant including Farrar&#039;s Island and environs as defined by 1637 patent]]\nAt the time of his death sometime before June 11, 1637, Farrar was described as being \"of Henrico\"<ref name=Nugent1934/>, one of eight [[shire|shires]] established in Virginia three years previously.<ref name=Hening1809/>{{rp|{{plainlink|https://archive.org/details/statutesatlargeb01invirg/page/224 224}}}}  By the time of his death, he had established his headright to a 2000 acre land patent at a site that included [[Dutch Gap]] and the former settlement of [[Henricus|Henrico]]. This headright was given for 40 indentured servants, who were named in the patent. {{notetag|At least seven of the names of the patents were those of people listed as living with Farrar and Jordan in the Muster of 1624/1625,{{refn|name=Southall1943}} many of the remaining names that can be traced through the Muster of 1624/1625 come from a wide variety of ships and times and have no clear connection to Jordan's Journey. After 1619, settlers could purchase the cost of shipping indentured servants to the new world as a contract that could redeemed as a headright.  The contracts could in turn be sold or traded to others.<ref name=Galenson1984/>}} After Farrar's death, the headright was repatented to his oldest son,<ref name=McCartney2011/> his namesake twelve years old at the time, by John Harvey, who had returned from England and resumed his role as governor of the colony.<ref name= Tarter2017b/>\n\nThe patent was issued for land that included a peninsula formed by [[meander]] loop, or curl,<ref name = McJimsey1940/>}} of the James River subsequently known as [[Farrar's Island]]. It is described in the patent as abutting the [[glebe]] lands of [[Varina Farms|Varina]] in the east,{{notetag|The glebe of Varina's boundaries were mapped during an archaeological study performed just before the construction of the [[Varina-Enon Bridge]] at the glebe's former location.<ref name=Geier&McCartney2018/>}} and extending to the James River in the south, the end of the island (i.e., peninsula) in the west, and \"to the woods\" in the north.<ref name=Nugent1934/>  Farrar's Island remained with the Farrar family until it was sold in 1731.<ref name=Stanard1901/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notefoot}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=Aughterson1998>{{cite book|editor=Aughterson, Kate|title=The English Renaissance: An Anthology of Sources and Documents|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uopDaWjyyekC&q=Westminster+#v=onepage&q=Westminster%2024%20August%201588&f=false|publisher=New York, NY: Routledge|year=1998|isbn=9780415271158|pp=201\u2013202}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Bancroft1888>{{cite book|title=History of the United States of America, Vol. I|author=Bancroft, George|author-link=George Bancroft|publisher=New York, NY: D. Appleton|date=1888|page=[https://archive.org/details/historyoftheunit037605mbp/page/n169 135]|url=https://archive.org/details/historyoftheunit037605mbp}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Bannerman1899>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/visitationsofcou43beno |title=The Visitations of the County of Surrey: Made and Taken in the Years 1530 by Thomas Benolte, Clarenceux King of Arms; 1572 by Robert Cooke, Clarenceux King of Arms; and 1623 by Samuel Thomson, Windsor Herald and Augustin Vincent, Rouge Croix Pursuivant, Marshals and Deputies to William Camden, Clarenceux King of Arms|year=1899|pp=[https://archive.org/details/visitationsofcou43beno/page/157 157]\u2013158|publisher= London: Ye Wardour|editor=Bannerman, W. Bruce}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Bemiss1957>{{cite book|title=The Three Charters of the Virginia Company of London with Seven Related Documents|chapter=Third Charter| editor=Bemiss, Samuel M.|date=1957|publisher=Williamsburg, VA: Virginia 350th Anniversary Celebration Corporation|chapter-url=https://www.gutenberg.org/files/36181/36181-h/36181-h.htm#pg_7|page=7}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Billings2013>{{cite web|last=Billings, Warren M.|date=27 October 2013|access-date=21 Dec 2018|url=https://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/West_Thomas_twelfth_baron_De_La_Warr_1577-1618|title= Thomas West, twelfth baron De La Warr (1576\u20131618)|website= Encyclopedia Virginia|publisher=Virginia Foundation for the Humanities}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Brown1890v1>{{cite book|author=Brown, Alexander|date=1890|title=Genesis of the United States, Vol. 1|publisher=New York: Houghton, Mifflin|page=[https://archive.org/details/TheGenesisOfTheUnitedStatesV1/page/n116 57]|url=https://archive.org/details/TheGenesisOfTheUnitedStatesV1|author-link=Alexander Brown (author)}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Brown1890v2>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/genesisofuniteds02brow/page/n455|title=The Genesis of the United States, Vol 2|last=Brown|first=Alexander|date=1890|publisher=Boston, MA Houghton, Mifflin|page=[https://archive.org/details/genesisofuniteds02brow/page/n455 691]|author-link=Alexander Brown (author)}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Brown1898\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/firstrepublicina01brow|title=The First Republic in America|last=Brown|first=Alexander|author-link=Alexander Brown (author)|publisher=Boston, MA: Houghton, Mifflin|year=1898|isbn=|pp=[https://archive.org/details/firstrepublicina01brow/page/645 645]\u2013648}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Brown1901>{{Cite book | last=Brown | first=Alexander|author-link=Alexander Brown (author)|title=English Politics in Early Virginia History |publication-date=1901 | publisher=Boston, MA: Houghton Mifflin |date=1901|page=[https://archive.org/details/englishpoliticsi00brow/page/100 100] | url=https://archive.org/details/englishpoliticsi00brow| quote=English politics in early virginia history William Ferrar. }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Bruce1894>{{cite journal |title= Mutiny in Virginia, 1635|editor= Bruce, Philip A.|author-link=Philip Alexander Bruce|url=https://archive.org/details/virginiamagazine01virguoft/page/418|journal=Virginia Magazine of History and Biography|volume=1|year=1894|issue=4|page=419}}</ref>\n\n<ref name= Campbell1860>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/historyofcolonya00campuoft/page/180|title=History of Colony and Ancient Dominion of Virginia|last=Campbell|first=Charles|publisher=J.Philadelphia, PA: B. Lippincott|year=1860}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Coldham1979\">{{cite journal |last=Coldham, Peter Wilson|author-link=Peter Wilson Coldham|date= 1979|title= The voyage of the Neptune to Virginia 1618-1619, and the Disposition of its cargo |jstor=4248277 |journal=The Virginia Magazine of History and Biography |volume=87 |issue=1 |pages=30\u201367}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Coldham2002>{{cite book|author=Coldham, Peter Wilson|author-link=Peter Wilson Coldham|title=English Adventurers and Emigrants, 1609-1660: Abstracts of Examinations in the High Court of Admiralty with Reference to Colonial America|pages=5-6|publisher=Baltimore, MD: Genealogical Publishing|date=2002|isbn=9780806310824|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/englishadventure00cold}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=CroxtonParish1583>{{cite web|title=Croxton Parish Records- Marriages, Baptisms & Burials (1583)|website= Lincs to the Past, Lincolnshire Archives|url=https://www.lincstothepast.com/Records/RecordDisplayTranscript.aspx?oid=723828&iid=180376|date=December 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Dorman2004>{{cite book | editor-last=Dorman, John Frederick | title=Adventurers of Purse and Person, Virginia, 1607\u20131624/5: Families A-F (Volume 1)| date=2004 | publisher=Baltimore, MD: Genealogical Publishing | edition= 4th.|pp=926\u2013928|isbn=978-0806317441}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=ElleMagazine2014>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.elle.com.au/celebrity/so-turns-out-the-fanning-sisters-are-royals-3452|magazine=Elle Australia|title=So, turns out the Fanning sisters are royals|date= 28 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191030210130/https://www.elle.com.au/celebrity/so-turns-out-the-fanning-sisters-are-royals-3452|archive-date=30 Oct 2019|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Fausz2013>{{Cite web|url=https://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Argall_Samuel_bap_1580-1626|title=Samuel Argall (bap. 1580-1626)|author= Fausz, J. Frederick|date=July 8, 2013|website=Encyclopedia Virginia: Virginia Humanities|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190115182012/https://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Argall_Samuel_bap_1580-1626|archive-date=January 15, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=January 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n.<ref name =Farrer1936>{{cite book|title=Farrer (and Some Variants) Wills and Administrations : So Far Discovered by Me in England and Wales, and the Isle of Man Down to A.D. 1800|author=Farrer, Thomas C. F|author-link= Thomas Farrer, 2nd Baron Farrer|date=1936|publisher=Dorking, England: Tanner and Son|pp=[https://archive.org/details/farrerandsomevar00farr/page/126 126]\u2013128|url=https://archive.org/details/farrerandsomevar00farr}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Galenson1984>{{cite journal |last=Galenson, David W.|author-link=David Galenson|date= 1984|title= The rise and fall of indentured servitude in the Americas: An economic analysis|jstor=2120553 |journal=The Journal of Economic History |volume=44 |issue=1 |page=10}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Geier&McCartney2018>{{Cite book|title=The Henrico Parish Glebe, Varina, Virginia: 44HE229, A Multidisciplinary Case Study|author1=Geier, Clarence R.|author2=McCartney, Martha W.|author2-link=Martha W. McCartney|volume=Special Publication no. 45|publisher=Richmond,VA:Archeological Society of Virginia|ISBN=1981435816|year=2018|page=3}}</ref>\n\n<ref name= Hatch1957>{{ Cite book |author= Hatch, Charles E.|year=1957|title=The First Seventeen Years: Virginia, 1607-1624|publisher=Williamsburg, VA: Jamestown 350th Anniversary Celebration Corp.|page=68|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/files/30780/30780-h/30780-h.htm#JORDAN_R}}</ref>\n\n<ref name= Hening1809>{{cite book|title= The Statutes at Large; Being a Collection of All the Laws of Virginia, from the Firs